      "writtenOn": "2020-12-08T15:38:36Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e I do like the way SkArenaAlloc branches on std::is_trivially_destructible\u003cT\u003e::value to handle this POD/non-POD distinction for you.  Surely it\u0027s compiling away as if a constexpr-if for different T, right?\n\u003e \nIt is compiling the constexpr-if out. I made the POD distinction because Ganesh uses POD data structures to make shortcuts in their code (basically not calling destructors). The SkArena API makes that practice safe and explicit. \n\n\u003e I guess the idea here is that you get a different type back?  But why not use a unique_ptr with destroyer in both cases?  The destroyer will no-op out for POD T.\nI did consider not having the makePOD case. It just results in a nop destroyer. But, this would make sharing the pointer in data structures a little confusing. You would get the unique_ptr back, and either call .release() to use the raw pointer, or use .get().",
      "parentUuid": "a36c52b8_df54a8a9",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 69,
        "startChar": 22,
        "endLine": 69,
        "endChar": 62
      },
      "revId": "ba51c314f753482191353d0bf7c84fbef8aa1cf2",
